I am proud to say that Cook County is moving towards more transparency and accountability.  We passed our Open Data Ordinance earlier today.
Under the plan, agencies will publish an Open Government Plan describing their path to more transparency, participation, and collaboration
Agencies will release at least 3 datasets, the first of many, within 120 days. The data can be used freely by the public for apps or review.
We'll have a new website, OpenCC.info, coming very soon.  It will be the home for more information on open government in Cook County.

Don't forget Thursday 6:30pm Public Hearing on #CookCounty budget 69 W. Washington, Chicago #telltoni
1st question: have you been satisfied with support from other elected officials in budget process?
Gibson: this year for the 1st time Cook County released a preliminary budget, this has allowed for engagement much earlier. #opengov
2nd question from Jennifer: future of Provident Hospital?
Preckwinkle: Strategic plan calls for turning Oak Forest into primary/specialty care center, likewise for Provident.
Submit your questions tonight at #telltoni
Q3: what about city-county collaboration?
Kurt Summers: 19 items proposed by joint City-County team. Examples: joint procurement, volume pricing for asphalt, paper etc
Summers: if City and County revenue departments can share data, can do a better job of revenue collection.
Q4:  pension reform? Preckwinkle: we are in a situation where generous benefits are expensive to government...
Live video townhall on Cook County budget now at http://t.co/1kxQthL
Q5: would sales tax have been able to balance the budget?  P: no, $250 million is "structural deficit", problem goes well beyond rollback
A. Gibson: first order of business is to look for cost reductions. P: efficiencies and streamlining. People can't absorb tax increases.
Reminder: submit questions online via #telltoni
Q6: Wilbon wants to know what TB Sanitarium does and can we save $6m there?
P: fund has a surplus of $21m now... G: this is a special purpose fund, self-supported by a revenue stream--34 like this--created by State
Q7: is County collecting all taxes due it?  P: as mentioned, city/county joint enforcement like cigarette stamps. Kurt: sharing data and...
...if you owe taxes or fines to one entity, info should be shared by license issuers, etc.
P: we have to figure out how as a society we can deal with addiction with programs, jobs, not jail--we spend $500m a year on CCounty jails
Q9 from Amesha: What can the County do to improve public safety?
TP: CeaseFire in 4 Chicago communities www.ceasefirechicago.org joint project of City, County and foundations.
Q11: what are we doing to help create jobs?  TP: our new County Bureau of Economic Development consolidated former depts, better focus
Q12 from Shelly: you are using technology tonight, what about increasing access to tech throughout the County?
KS: looking at joint County-State project to extend broadband to underserved parts of #cookcounty
Few minutes left to ask questions online #townhall with Toni Preckwinkle use #telltoni http://t.co/1kxQthL
Q from @johnfritchey: layoffs, furloughs in FY12?  Andrea: right now looking at non-personnel, but 80% of budget is personnel
KS: maybe we also need to look at saving money by bringing some work in house; TP: we've invited unions to discuss
Thanks to all for participating tonight in online Cook County #townhall
